The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 L amp;T net earnings jump to Rs 157 cr

 OUR CORRESPONDENT 

 Mumbai, July 21: Larsen amp; Toubro Ltd (L amp;T) has posted a 50 per cent growth in net profit at Rs 157.13 crore for the first quarter of the current fiscal against Rs 104.79 crore in the corresponding period last year.

 However, during the first quarter of 2005-06, the company had made a profit of Rs 38.18 crore from sale of business. Taking that into account, the companys net profit for the quarter year-on-year has gone up by 9.9 per cent.

 Gross sales of the company went up by 12.5 per cent to Rs 3,523.83 crore for the quarter against Rs 3,131.75 crore in the corresponding period last fiscal. International operations contributed 17 per cent of the gross revenues for the quarter.

 The engineering and construction segment has recorded an 8 per cent growth in gross revenues at Rs 2,618.88 crore against Rs 2,424.65 crore in the same period last fiscal. Export sales for the current quarter constituted 19 per cent of the total segment revenue.

 Profit before interest and taxes for the segment has increased by 92 per cent to Rs 199.10 crore. The segment has achieved a growth of 121 per cent in order booking at Rs 6,324 crore during the quarter, of which international orders constitute 16 per cent. 

 The revenue from electrical and electronics segment has grown by 31 per cent at Rs 424.38 crore for the current quarter, while the profit before interest and taxes has increased by 68 per cent to Rs 67 crore for the quarter. 

 The machinery and industrial products segment has achieved a 5 per cent growth in revenues for the quarter at Rs 336.83 crore. however, higher price realisations and improved product mix have resulted in 86 per cent increase in profitability. 

 According to the company, sustained high oil prices and global demand have boosted investment plans across sectors, particularly in the areas of hydrocarbons and other core sector industries. 

 However, L amp;Ts stock price today declined by 5.23 per cent in a weak market. 

 The stock closed at Rs 2,022.35 on the Bombay Stock Exchange, down Rs 111.65 from yesterdays Rs 2,134 amidst a volume of over two lakh shares. 




